rstanding of the fundamental sciences underpinning health, optical and vision sciences.</li> <li>Perform common optical and visual diagnostic assessments.</li> <li>Learn about anatomy, physiology and neuroscience of the visual system.</li> <li>Explore health sciences, business and management to broaden your expertise.</li> <li>Get hands-on training and have opportunities to work in the state-of-the-art University of Canberra Hospital.</li> <li>Collaborate with academics and clinicians who are actively engaged in research and practice.</li> <li>Demonstrate awareness of and respect for individual human rights and cultural and social diversity.</li> </ul> <h4>Study your way</h4> <p>This optometry course is available on campus, supported by hands-on labs and clinical exposure. You’ll experience a balance of theory, practical learning and applied projects, with supportive teaching designed to build your confidence step by step.</p> <h4>Work Integrated Learning (WIL)</h4> <p>At UC, Work Integrated Learning is part of every degree. In Vision Science, this could mean laboratory work, research projects or engagement with community health initiatives. Through your optometrist training, these experiences will help you apply classroom learning to real challenges and ensure you graduate confident and job-ready.</p> <p>In your final year, you''ll enrol in the work-integrated unit <em>Integrated Eye Care and Ocular Therapeutics</em>. This unit incorporates a significant component of industry experience, including clinical and non-clinical placements, designed to observe the latest vision science industry projects and optometric practice in progress.</p> <h4>Career opportunities</h4> <ul> <li>Optometrist (with completion of the Master of Optometry)</li> <li>Optical or vision science researcher</li> <li>Ophthalmic or optical industry specialist</li> <li>Public health and vision care advocate</li> <li>Clinical or laboratory technician</li> <li>Private practice and retailer</li> <li>Health services manager</li> </ul> <h4>Professional accreditation</h4> <p>This course is accredited with the Optometry Council of Australia and New Zealand (OCANZ). Successful completion of both the Bachelor of Vision Science AND the Master of Optometry course at the University of Canberra will allow graduates the chance to apply for registration with the Optometry Board of Australia to practice as an optometrist. <br/> <br/>Please note that the Master of Optometry (374JA) is Fee Paying from 2024.</p> </div> </div>',
